trades.notes: Continuation of strong reaction to 5m GAP. Large bearish candles added confluence to go short. No HULK signal; entry candle formation had no wick in direction of trade (momentum still bearish). Happy with execution. Emotions were fear-based: didn’t want to lose profit from earlier trade. Felt I exited too early initially, but on review it was the right decision because it wasn’t an A+ entry signal, so needed to manage tightly and protect account/position. Compared to a later setup I didn’t take after hitting daily TP: clean HULK candle, where SL management would have been more accommodating to let trade run to full TP.

Almost A+ entry shown on GC. Had the bullish break and retest of lower VWAP. Entry candle was just above lower VWAP band (strategy states that it should be touching). This combined with the WAE above Dead Zone, London session opening volatility / volume, validated entry.

Executed well, kept composed throughout trade.

Felt price had enough momentum to go +2R, however struggled with the different price levels between MGC and GC. Due to this slight error, I missed the full TP and finished around 1R.

Not much I can do about this, one of the realities of trading a smaller timeframe, and limitations of human execution etc.

Most important take away is the psychological aspect. I had to really focus on not feeling 'cheated' and tipping into TILT. Had to remind myself of staying composed and my purpose. Being professional and treating trading as a business.

Good entry signal with confluence from a bullish 5-min Hulk candle close. Slight slippage impacted R:R. Price didn’t reach TP before pulling back to breakeven first, so you were taken out at BE. Overall entry and trade process were good; you stayed composed. Part of the game—sometimes it pulls back before continuing.

Slight deviation on entry: candle wasn’t touching the upper VWAP band, but it was very strong/bullish so you entered expecting continuation off the middle VWAP band with NY volume pushing higher. Price then stagnated. You moved stop loss up more than necessary. Decision was influenced by being over-risked again (didn’t learn from prior trade), which led to tinkering with the trade/stop. If left alone, it would have been a clear/easy TP. Lesson: execution and mental process still a bit rusty; needs work.

OK setup, not the strongest bullish Hulk candle for a break of the upper VWAP band. Main issue: over-risked due to large contract size (Gold + NY session volatility). At normal risk ($200–$250) it would’ve been acceptable, but position sizing made the mistake costly. Trade was a loss anyway. Execution not great; didn’t really need to be in this trade after already taking a NY win. Lesson: learn when to stop/leave it and take what the market gave.

Clear re-entry. Wouldn’t have needed it if prior trade hadn’t slipped. Strong bearish entry candle: bearish Hulk closing below VWAP band; prior candle also very bearish with strong wick. Took entry and managed well. Clear target: London session low. Stayed focused/composed though a bit gutted about the previous trade; felt direction was clear (highs taken, then likely NY takes lows). Nerve-wracking retrace before London low was taken—price came back to lower VWAP band; debated closing but held on. Price then resumed and took the lows. Overall good trade.

Very strong bearish Hulk entry candle + histogram flip; momentum/histogram highest of the day. Entry candle broke the VWAP band and the VWAP band itself. ES rejection of Asia highs + HOD added confluence, so signal was clear. Problem: NY open volatility caused slippage so entry was poor and risk/stop got larger than intended. Moved stop behind the second candle; retrace/wick stopped out. Overall happy with read and attempt; 1-min volatility/slippage impacted R:R.

Entry not ideal. Saw bearish momentum and thought continuation down likely. No clear bearish “Hulk” candle, but strong rejection from upper VWAP band gave confidence to short. Managed tightly: after a clear break down, moved stop to breakeven ASAP. Volatility was high and move wasn’t as strong as hoped; would have been a full stop without tightening. Happy with management despite messy entry.

Valid re-entry bouncing off upper VWAP band. Many bottom wicks suggesting upside continuation. Hulk bullish entry candle + WAE histogram flip confirmed. But context issue: ES trade had already played out profitably; had just been stopped out of prior NQ trade. Entered anyway due to greed/forcing and overconfidence about where market would go. Entry itself fine, but trade was unnecessary given prior stop-out and ES already delivered.

Entry signal OK. Stop-loss management OK. Issue: already in ES, so overall risk was too high (over-risked). NQ had already taken Asia highs + HOD so upside was more limited vs ES. Execution followed plan, but in hindsight should have stuck with ES only.

A+ setup. Strong “Hulk” entry candle with minimal upper wick. VWAP band squeeze pre-NY open; NY open brought volume/volatility. Entered well, managed well, prepped well. Targets: Asia highs then prior day highs; let it stretch. Good stop.

reviews.ai_insight: Stats: 9 trades, Net P/L -120.00, Win rate 33.3%, Avg Efficiency 2.89 (above 2.0 target), Cost of Errors -640.00. Behavioral patterns: (1) Edge shows when you pick best market/setup and execute cleanly (T2 template). (2) Biggest leak was not entries but risk and interference: exposure stacking (ES+NQ) and repeated over-risking (notably T8/T9) led to stop tinkering and trading P/L rather than the trade. (3) Emotional sequencing: after a win or stop-out you pressed (greed/forcing/overconfidence in T4), turning an otherwise fine day into error-cost. Key rule: if you feel over-risked, reduce size or do not trade; over-size reliably triggers micromanagement and collapses edge.
reviews.user_reflection: Noted that early-session greed and subsequent mistakes need to be sat with rather than “pushed for more.” Recognized a repeating pattern over recent sessions: make mistakes/go into drawdown, then over-risk and try to trade out of drawdown instead of stopping to reset and review plan, execution, and composure. Chose to stop for the day to reset. Intends to focus on basics next session: trade smaller (e.g., 1 contract), no stress, take only clear entries, and avoid the mindset of making it back. London session was traded poorly due to lack of prep and not dealing with losses, leading to trying to compensate in NY in a performance sense; wants to be more professional and handle losing properly.

reviews.ai_insight: Week 2025-12-15 to 2025-12-21: Net +1845.00 on 39 trades with 51.3% win rate, but Efficiency Score 0.54 (below 2.0 target) and Cost of Errors -1085.00 show a profitable week achieved with significant self-inflicted leakage. Notes show two modes: when executing well you are patient and let trades work; when impatience appears you force entries without signal, trade chop, and can slide into tilt (notably 2025-12-17: repeated ‘no signal/forced’ entries -> chasing -> breaking session rules -> trading until lockout/DD). Another recurring theme is inconsistency in protection/management when right (hesitation to move stop to BE) and P/L-protection psychology (fear of giving back profits leading to hesitation, then later forcing). Priority is eliminating ‘no-signal’ trades and having pre-decided management rules to prevent the impatience-to-tilt cascade.
reviews.user_reflection: Although I had mistakes and moments of weakness / poor trading etc. I'm glad in the end that I was able to overcome them and end up net positive. So many times previous, I had let negative days affect me so badly that it would just get continually worse - eventually failing multiple challenges etc. Now I feel like I'm really focused on learning to 'lose' so to speak, making mistakes but remembering that they will happen and I just need to focus on being consistent and doing the right things, day in day out. Next week I want to continue this pattern and become even better than last week in terms of composure, execution etc.

reviews.ai_insight: Strong day in process and emotional control: repeated notes of calm, patience, and composure aligned with high efficiency (3.67) and zero cost of errors. You executed a consistent thesis (Asia low) and accepted when the flush didn’t materialize via disciplined BE management. Watch the one potential crack: resizing/adding because “risk wasn’t enough.” Ensure scaling rules are pre-defined rather than emotion-led. Keep using BE as a confirmation-based protection tool, not as discomfort avoidance.
reviews.user_reflection: Thoughts for today follows much of what was said in the trade notes. Felt on point, felt composed and just ready to trade. Not overly emotional. I hope to keep the mind frame and composure for next session, and the session after that. Eventually let it be my baseline and really start getting consistent with my trading.

reviews.ai_insight: Net profitable week but very low efficiency (0.36 vs target >2.0), suggesting overtrading/chop exposure and entries not aligned with core strategy. Notes indicate a pattern: missing an early trade triggers urgency/chasing, followed by repeated stop-outs; awareness of needing to walk away but continuing to trade; and revenge trading rationalized as “confluence.” Key risk is emotional escalation after a losing day leading to TILT and historically large drawdowns/account damage. Primary focus: protect mindset first—implement a mandatory reset protocol after missed trades or first significant emotional spike; prioritize selectivity and execution quality over participation.
reviews.user_reflection: Yes definitely felt this. I have noticed that I can trade ok and be profitable for a few days, even weeks, however I am not trading effciently or inline with my strategy. Then I have a losing day, which typically sets me off and I end up on TILT. Often blowing my account. My goals for next week are to keep composed, keep consistent, focus on execution and being a 'professional trader' who understands the market isn't about winning, its about process, day in day out.
